Storage class speciﬁers are keywords that can be used in declarations. They do not aﬀect the type of the

declaration, but typically modify the way in which the entity is stored.

Section 133.1: extern

The extern storage class speciﬁer can modify a declaration in one of the three following ways, depending on

context:

1.

It can be used to declare a variable without deﬁning it. Typically, this is used in a header ﬁle for a variable that

will be deﬁned in a separate implementation ﬁle.

// global scope
int x;             // definition; x will be default-initialized
extern int y;      // declaration; y is defined elsewhere, most likely another TU
extern int z = 42; // definition; "extern" has no effect here (compiler may warn)

2.

It gives external linkage to a variable at namespace scope even if const or constexpr would have otherwise

caused it to have internal linkage.

